Data Visualization Exercise¶

For this exercise, use your creativity and understanding of the different concepts of data visualization.

Create a plot (or a series of subplots) from whatever dataset you choose. As much as possible, please choose a dataset of relevance for visual storytelling. Make the plot using python. It doesn't matter if you choose to use matplotlib or seaborn.

For the submission:

  1. Upload the code that generates the plot to your GitHub repository or to Google Classroom (whichever method you're using for submissions).
  2. Upload a png file of the visualization to Google Classroom and write in the Private Comments the caption for the figure you submitted.
  3. Make sure to provide the data source in the same folder.

Please make an effort to make it a good and compelling graphic. Choose your colors according to the type of data you're visualizing. Make sure to label everything and avoid clutter.

As a reference for color choices, you can go to CARTOColors. Simply click on the color map of your choice and it will copy the HEX code of the color.

How happy are our coutries?¶

In [8]:
# Visualize your data

ax = df['score'].hist(edgecolor='w', figsize=(12, 7), color='#E7E4CB',bins=7, width=0.7) ##b5ead7 F58C5F

ax.set_title('Distribution of Countries based on Happiness Score', color='#006680', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
ax.set_xlabel('Score', color='#006680', fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel('No. of Countries', color='#006680', fontsize=15);

ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.xaxis.grid(False)
ax.yaxis.grid(False)

ax.axvline(x=df['score'].mean(), color='#164066', linestyle='--', label='mean') #linestyle can -- .- -.
ax.axvline(x=df['score'].median(), color='#25C5BF', linewidth=4, label='median')
ax.legend(fontsize=14);
In [9]:
import seaborn as sns, numpy as np

fig_dims = (12, 7)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_dims)

sns.distplot(df['score'], color='#E7E4CB', bins=7, hist_kws={"rwidth":1,'edgecolor':'white', 'alpha':1.0})
sns.set(style="white")

ax.set_title('Distribution of Countries based on Happiness Score', color='#006680', fontweight='bold', fontsize=20,)
ax.set_xlabel('Score', color='#006680', fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel('No. of Countries', color='#006680', fontsize=15);

ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.xaxis.grid(False)

ax.axvline(x=df['score'].mean(), color='#164066', linestyle='--', label='mean') #linestyle can -- .- -.
ax.axvline(x=df['score'].median(), color='#25C5BF', linewidth=4, label='median')
ax.legend(fontsize=14);

Caption: The two figures above provide the distribution of countries based on the World Happiness Report score. Two different methods were used - histplot and distplot. Both figures also identify the close values of the mean and median.

cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 10, as_cmap=True) #set the plot structure

fig_dims = (12, 7)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_dims)
ax = df.groupby('continent')['score'].mean().sort_values().plot(kind='bar',figsize=(10,6), width=0.8, cmap=cmap)

ax.set_title('Happiness Score per Continent', color='#006680', fontweight='bold', fontsize=20,)
ax.set_ylabel('Score', color='#006680',)
ax.set_xlabel('')
ax.set_xticklabels(['Europe', 'Oceania', 'North America', 'Asia', 'South America', 'Africa'], rotation=0, color='#006680', fontsize=15);

ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.xaxis.grid(False)

Caption: The figure above represents the mean average happiness score per continent. Oceania has the highest average of happiness score among the countries. One factor that may also cause this is the limited number of observations (only two) under this continent. The next continent with highest happiness score is North America.

Correlation of factors against each other¶

How does one factor relate to another?

In [13]:
df2 = df.drop(['rank', 'score'], 1) #drop as rank and score are dependent variables
sns.set(style="white")

rs = np.random.RandomState(33)
d = pd.DataFrame(data=rs.normal(size=(100, 26)),
                  columns=list(ascii_letters[26:]))

corr = df2.corr() #get corr values
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=np.bool)) #mask the upper triangle
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9)) #set the plot structure
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 10, as_cmap=True) #set the plot structure

sns.heatmap(corr, mask=mask, cmap=cmap, vmax=.3, center=0,
           square=True, linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={"shrink": .5}) #overall

ax.set_title('Correlation matrix of the factors', fontweight='bold',fontsize=20,)
ax.set_ylabel('')
ax.set_xlabel('') 
ax.xaxis.grid(False)
In [14]:
plt.figure(figsize=(11,9))
sns.set(style="white")
sns.heatmap(df2.corr(), annot=True, cmap=cmap)
plt.show()

Caption: The two figures above show the correlation matrix of all the factors. We have dropped rank and score from the matrix as these are both dependent variables. The first matrix is only dependent on the shade of the colors whereas the second matrix also provides the actual correlation value.

Does a better economy also mean a happier country?¶

fig_dims = (12, 7)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_dims)

sns.regplot(x='score',y='population', data=df)
sns.set(style="white")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

ax.set_title('Correlation between happiness score and population', color='#006680', fontweight='bold', fontsize=20,)
ax.set_ylabel('Population', color='#006680', fontsize=15);
ax.set_xlabel('Happiness Score', color='#006680', fontsize=15);

ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
ax.xaxis.grid(False)

Caption: The figure above aims to check the correlation between population and happines score. Population difference has no impact in the score.

In [18]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)

groups = df.groupby("continent")
for name, group in groups:
    plt.plot(group["GDP_per_cap"], group["score"], marker="o", linestyle='', label=name, ms=10, alpha=0.7)

ax.set_xlabel('GDP per capita', color='#006680', fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel('Score', color='#006680', fontsize=15)
ax.set_title('Happiness Score vs. GDP per capita per continent', color='#006680', fontweight='bold', fontsize=20,);

plt.legend()

# Saving visualized data
fig.savefig('Happiness Score vs. GDP per capita_Rebong_Maria Concepcion.png')

Caption: The figure above is a scatterplot showing the correlation between the country's happines score and its GDP per capita, grouped by continent. We can observe than most of the Africa countries are on the lower left quadrant whereas most of the Europe countries are on the upper right quadrant.
